				<div class="postbody">
				I have a couple tried and true methods for determining at a short glance the usablility of software solutions.  Its related to how I judge technical books where I compare the amount of pages devoted to indexing and appendixes in ratio to the rest of te book.
<br />

<br />
Books with less than 10% of their pages devoted to helping you find information are rated very poorly.  The author and or the publisher have clearly shown that they did not have the reader in mind when they layed out the book.  The book may have loads of good information in it but if you cant find what you need what good is it?
<br />

<br />
When looking at a new mfg of software I look for what kind of support information is available. If there is a problem how fast can I find what kind of information to get me up and going again quickly.
<br />

<br />
Companies that have easy to find and extensive support pages tend to also be companies that test and verify their products before release.  Companies that only have one page devoted to talking you into buying more "support options" have only one thing in mind in my experience:
<br />

<br />
Taking you for every dollar they can in support costs.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
I have no experience with this software nor the company.  I, myself, would like to find a replacement for Exchange that would convert seemlessly.  But their online presence is so thin that I cannot even tell what their product is supposed to do.
<br />

<br />
I'd stay far away.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
