			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Your seamless replacement for Exchange is <a href="http://www.suse.com/us/business/products/openexchange/" target="_blank" class="postlink">right here,</a> with a working demo <a href="http://www.suse.com/us/business/products/openexchange/demo.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">right here.</a>
<br />

<br />
It'll talk to Outlook via the Exchange connector, so you can use Outlook (in Exchange server mode), Ximian (the GPL outlook clone), or any web browser for your email and groupware. It's far cheaper than outlook and exchange (and far more secure), but it is not free. As for a seamless integration, I'm willing to bet that a MS Exchange expert and a Linux expert could pull off a seamless migration given a couple of weeks and new hardware so they can do a live upgrade (unplugging the old system's network cable and plugging it into the new system). For a project like that only a madman takes his old system offline until after the new one has been working seamlessly for weeks.
<br />

<br />
Note, I have not done this myself (yet). I'm going to be setting up one in a couple of weeks at home for funsies, and then I'll have a much better idea how it works and how well it interoperates. Novell will also be releasing groupware and directory services for linux soon, and they will amost certainly have the best-of-breed groupware for linux. It's their specialty, after all.
<br />

<br />
It has been my experience with Linux that most of the time, using a general distro (like RedHat or SuSE) for all purposes is not the best way to go. There are a large number of targeted linux distributions out there (such as <a href="http://www.smoothwall.org/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Smoothwall</a> and <a href="http://www.sentinix.org/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Sentinix</a>) that are built with a specific task in mind, and they far exceed their generalized counterparts in both ease of use, security, and features, <span style="font-style: italic">for that specific task only.</span> If a distro exists to specifically serve one need you have, then it's best to use that distro to do that one task, and have 15 distros running at once instead of 15 custom-hacked versions of one distro. They are all still linux; administration skills are no different between distros and any competent linux admin will have no problem maintaining them.
<br />

<br />
Nitix at least has a <a href="http://www.net-itech.com/trynitix/seeit.php" target="_blank" class="postlink">demo,</a> which is good because any linux company that hasn't got one or a live-eval of some kind will not be taken seriously. From what I see there, they are a general purpose distro (like RedHat and SuSE) with a few slick web widgets, most of which are similar to the existing <a href="http://www.webmin.com/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Webmin</a> package. I don't see antyhing new there that makes me want to try it.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
